#: ../../source/techniques/configuration.rst:4
msgid ""
"The applications used to run in different **environments**. Depending on "
"an environment, various sets of configuration variables should be used. "
"For example, that‚Äôs very likely that local environment relies on specific"
" database credentials, valid solely for local db instance. In order to "
"solve this issue, we used to take advantage of ``.env`` files, that hold "
"key-value pairs, where each key represents a particular value since this "
"approach is very convenient."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/configuration.rst:12
msgid ""
"But when we use a ``process`` global object, it‚Äôs difficult to keep our "
"tests clean since tested class may directly use it. Another way is to "
"create an abstraction layer, a ``ConfigModule`` that exposes a "
"``ConfigService`` with loaded configuration variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/configuration.rst:18
msgid "Installation"
msgstr "Installation"

#: ../../source/techniques/configuration.rst:20
msgid ""
"Certain platforms automatically attach our environment variables to the "
"``process.env`` global. However, in the local environment, we have to "
"manually take care of it. In order to parse our environment files, we‚Äôll "
"use a `dotenv <https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv>`__ package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/configuration.rst:31
msgid "Service"
msgstr "Service"

#: ../../source/techniques/configuration.rst:33
msgid "Firstly, let‚Äôs create a ``ConfigService`` class."
msgstr "Firstly, let‚Äôs create a ``ConfigService`` class."

#: ../../source/techniques/configuration.rst:66
msgid ""
"This class takes a single argument, a ``filePath``, which is a path to "
"your ``.env`` file. The ``get()`` method is provided to enable access to "
"a private ``envConfig`` object that holds each property defined inside an"
" environment file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/configuration.rst:71
msgid "The last step is to create a ``ConfigModule``."
msgstr "The last step is to create a ``ConfigModule``."

#: ../../source/techniques/configuration.rst:90
msgid ""
"The ``ConfigModule`` registers a ``ConfigService`` and exports it as "
"well. Additionally, we passed a path to the ``.env`` file. This path will"
" be different depending on actual execution environment. Now you can "
"simply inject ``ConfigService`` anywhere, and pull out a particular value"
" based on a passed key. Sample ``.env`` file could look like below:"
